 {"id": "franken_networkx-chordalcliquetypes", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] chordal_graph_cliques returned list of lists; nx yields generator of frozensets", "description": "nx.chordal_graph_cliques yields (as a generator) frozensets of nodes forming maximal cliques of the chordal graph, and is @not_implemented_for('directed','multigraph'). fnx returned a plain list of lists and silently accepted directed/multigraph inputs. Callers that did ``next(r)`` or set-ops on the cliques diverged. Fixed the wrapper to: (a) raise NetworkXNotImplemented with nx's exact messages for directed / multigraph inputs, (b) wrap the Rust list-of-lists into a generator that yields frozensets. Verified ``iter(r) is r`` and round-tripped cliques match nx element-for-element.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T16:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T16:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T16:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Gate type + generator-of-frozensets", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-loadcent", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] load_centrality returned betweenness_centrality as a shortcut; Newman's load differs in practice", "description": "fnx.load_centrality's (cutoff=None, weight=None) fast path returned betweenness_centrality(G) directly. While often described as equivalent for unweighted graphs, Newman's load algorithm counts path fractions differently when multiple shortest paths share intermediate nodes \u2014 on the karate club graph the two diverged on 18/34 nodes by ~1-5% (node 0: fnx/betweenness=0.4376 vs nx/load=0.4347). Dropped the shortcut and routed every case through _load_centrality_from_source_local, which already mirrors nx._node_betweenness exactly (predecessor-based reverse-BFS accumulation). Verified 0/34 diffs on karate (unweighted and weighted) and on the 4-node MultiGraph test fixture.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T16:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T16:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T16:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Native Newman's load impl via _load_centrality_from_source_local", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-onionlayers", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] onion_layers diverged from nx on karate (3 nodes placed one layer too high)", "description": "fnx's Rust onion_layers_rust placed karate nodes 1, 3, 13 in layer 7 where nx places them in layer 6, and the global layer-count distribution differed (fnx {7:5, 6:1, ...} vs nx {7:2, 6:4, ...}). Route through nx's reference implementation via a private _onion_layers_impl helper (keeps public classifier as PY_WRAPPER). Verified 0 diffs on karate and C3/C5/C10.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T16:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T16:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T16:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate to nx via _onion_layers_impl", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-cnlti-tiebreak", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] convert_node_labels_to_integers 'increasing/decreasing degree' broke ties differently from nx", "description": "nx sorts (degree, node) tuples (breaking ties by node value); fnx used ``sorted(G.nodes(), key=lambda n: G.degree[n])`` which is a stable-by-degree sort and preserved original iteration order on ties. That produced a different int mapping on any graph with degree ties (e.g. a 3-node path with identical-degree leaves, or any regular graph). Fix: build (d, n) tuple list and tuple-sort to match nx's tie-break exactly. Verified on tied-degree graphs (3-node path and cycle_graph).", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T16:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T16:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T16:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Tuple-sort to break ties by node", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-mladjdata", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] generate/write_multiline_adjlist silently dropped all edge attributes", "description": "G.adjacency() yields (node, AtlasView). The old code tested ``isinstance(adj, dict)`` which was False for AtlasView (fnx's own adj-view class), so it fell into the list-comprehension branch that hardcoded ``{}`` as the edge data. Every write_multiline_adjlist output therefore had ``{}`` in the attr slot regardless of the actual edge attributes \u2014 a major data-loss defect for any downstream consumer that reparses the file. Switched to ``hasattr(adj, 'items')`` and materialize dict(attrs) per neighbor; added an explicit multigraph branch that expands parallel edges as separate neighbor lines (matching nx's format). Verified fnx output now byte-matches nx (modulo the date-comment header) on Graph and MultiGraph fixtures.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T16:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T16:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T16:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Use items() + explicit multigraph branch", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-mladjreadattrs", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] parse/read_multiline_adjlist dropped edge attributes on the read side too", "description": "The multiline adjlist parser split each neighbor line and kept only parts[0] as the neighbor, silently dropping the edge attribute dict written in the remainder (format: '<nbr> {...}'). Round-tripping an nx-written file through fnx.read_multiline_adjlist therefore lost every edge attribute. Fix: split once (preserve the remainder), then use ast.literal_eval to parse the trailing dict back into edge attrs. Also supports the legacy bare-numeric edgetype form ('<nbr> <edge_value>') via the ``edgetype`` parameter. Round-trip now preserves {'weight': 5}, {'color': 'red'}, and bare-float attrs.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T16:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T16:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T16:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Parse trailing attr-dict via ast.literal_eval", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
